1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:06,650
In this video we are going to learn anemic domain model and rich domain model entities in domain driven

2
00:00:06,650 --> 00:00:07,280
design.

3
00:00:07,580 --> 00:00:14,210
In domain driven design, the concepts of the anemic domain model and rich domain model are crucial

4
00:00:14,210 --> 00:00:18,770
in understanding how domain logic is encapsulated in your entities.

5
00:00:19,040 --> 00:00:23,000
Before starting, I would like to ask questions for order entity.

6
00:00:23,030 --> 00:00:29,420
If you open the order entity, you can see that we have encapsulated order items is a private read only

7
00:00:29,420 --> 00:00:30,500
variable.

8
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:35,930
And now how can we add or remove new items into order aggregate?

9
00:00:36,290 --> 00:00:42,950
We know that order item is one to end relation with the order aggregate, but we should add and remove

10
00:00:42,950 --> 00:00:46,130
items in the order item for the specific order.

11
00:00:46,130 --> 00:00:47,750
So how can we do that?

12
00:00:47,750 --> 00:00:50,450
If you make the order items as a public?

13
00:00:50,540 --> 00:00:57,320
Everyone can add and remove items in this list, so we should not make the public for the order items.

14
00:00:57,320 --> 00:01:01,340
Everyone to edit the order items with reaching the order.

15
00:01:01,340 --> 00:01:06,350
So we have to encapsulate these add and remove item operations in the order itself.

16
00:01:06,350 --> 00:01:11,510
Because these add and remove item operations belongs to order domain aggregates.

17
00:01:11,900 --> 00:01:18,320
To understand these operations well, I'm going to come back to slide and explain what is anemic domain

18
00:01:18,320 --> 00:01:19,310
model entity.

19
00:01:19,340 --> 00:01:25,580
An anemic domain model is characterized by entities that have little or no business logic.

20
00:01:25,580 --> 00:01:27,920
That means that has no domain logic.

21
00:01:27,920 --> 00:01:33,590
And these entities are essentially data structures with getters and setter methods.

22
00:01:33,590 --> 00:01:39,950
But the business rules and the behaviors are typically implemented outside the entity, often in service

23
00:01:39,950 --> 00:01:40,550
layer.

24
00:01:41,410 --> 00:01:42,850
Here you can see the example.

25
00:01:42,850 --> 00:01:50,260
In this example, the order class is anemic because it only contains data and lacks of any domain logic

26
00:01:50,260 --> 00:01:51,190
or behavior.

27
00:01:52,180 --> 00:01:53,260
So what is rich?

28
00:01:53,260 --> 00:01:59,560
Domain model entity A rich domain model entity is an approach where the entity is encapsulated both

29
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:01,150
data and behavior.

30
00:02:01,240 --> 00:02:07,240
This model enriched entities with methods that embody business rules and domain logic.

31
00:02:07,600 --> 00:02:11,830
Here you can see an example of the rich domain model with the order.

32
00:02:11,830 --> 00:02:19,180
Entity order is a rich domain model as it include methods add order item and remove order item, which

33
00:02:19,180 --> 00:02:22,600
encapsulate the business logic for manipulating the order items.

34
00:02:23,290 --> 00:02:29,560
So if you compare with the anemic versus rich domain model, you can see the image at y axis.

35
00:02:29,560 --> 00:02:36,280
We can see workers and complexity and x axis we can see time and sadness.

36
00:02:36,490 --> 00:02:42,340
As you can see the image, you can see that anemic model starting very less efforts if you compare with

37
00:02:42,340 --> 00:02:43,510
the rich domain model.

38
00:02:43,510 --> 00:02:50,320
But when the time goes anemic model is going to more complex and spanning more workers and leading to

39
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:50,980
sadness.

40
00:02:51,430 --> 00:02:56,560
So if you compare with the anemic and rich domain model, we can start with the anemic domain model.

41
00:02:56,560 --> 00:03:01,240
Business logic is scattered across the application, often in services.

42
00:03:01,240 --> 00:03:08,290
Entities are simple data containers and easier to understand initially, but it can lead to issues with

43
00:03:08,290 --> 00:03:11,680
maintainability and understanding the business logic by time.

44
00:03:12,130 --> 00:03:18,310
And if you look at the rich domain model, it encapsulates the business logic within the entities more

45
00:03:18,310 --> 00:03:24,190
closely, represent the real world business domain, and it can be more complex to design, but leads

46
00:03:24,190 --> 00:03:26,890
to a more maintainable and cohesive model.

47
00:03:27,160 --> 00:03:32,710
So for our ordered domain aggregate, the goal should be to create a rich domain model.

48
00:03:32,710 --> 00:03:38,620
This involves encapsulating the logic for adding or removing orderitem objects within the order class

49
00:03:38,620 --> 00:03:39,370
itself.

50
00:03:39,370 --> 00:03:44,800
This encapsulation ensures that the operation follow the business rules and invariants of the order

51
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:45,490
aggregate.

52
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:51,070
Here you can see that we can add the two methods, including the add Order item and remove order item

53
00:03:51,070 --> 00:03:56,530
to perform the order item, related operations and business logic inside of these functions under the

54
00:03:56,530 --> 00:03:58,240
order aggregate entity class.

